<dl class="specification-list">

        <dt>Identification and Creation</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
            <dt>Object Number</dt>
            <dd>1979.110</dd>

                            <dt>People</dt>
                <dd>
                                                                 <a href=https://www.harvardartmuseums.org/collections/person/35105>Ferdinand-Victor-Eugène Delacroix</a>, French                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          (Charenton Saint-Maurice France 1798 - 1863 Paris France)
                                            <br>
                                    </dd>
            
                            <dt>Title</dt>
                <dd>Sketch after Goya's "Caprichos"</dd>
            
                                                                                                            
                            <dt>Classification</dt>
                <dd>Drawings</dd>
                                        <dt>Work Type</dt>
                <dd>
                                                            drawing                                                      </dd>
                                        <dt>Date</dt>
                <dd>c. 1824</dd>
                                                                <dt>Culture</dt>
                <dd>French</dd>
                            <dt>Persistent Link</dt>
                <dd><a href="https://hvrd.art/o/295291">https://hvrd.art/o/295291</a></dd>
          </dl>
        </dd>

        
                <dt>Physical Descriptions</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
                          <dt>Medium</dt>
              <dd>Brown ink on off-white laid paper, laid down</dd>
            
           
           
                          <dt>Dimensions</dt>
              <dd>22.1 x 18 cm (8 11/16 x 7 1/16 in.)</dd>
            
            
            
            
            
            
          </dl>
        </dd>
        
                  <dt>Provenance</dt>
          <dd>Louis Dimier (1865-1943) (Lugt 1721c), Paris, sold; through his sale [December 15, 1921, lot 31 as by Goya]. Léon Voillemot (1881-1949) (Lugt 789d), Paris. [1] Alfred Strölin, Paris], sold; to Philip and Frances L. Hofer, Cambridge, Massachusetts; bequest of Frances L. Hofer, 1979<br />
<br />
Notes<br />
[1] There was no public sale following Voillemot's sale but he did sell a number of works during a period of illness.</dd>
        
        
        
        <dt>Acquisition and Rights</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
                          <dt>Credit Line</dt>
              <dd>Harvard Art Museums/Fogg Museum, Bequest of Frances L. Hofer</dd>
            
            
                          <dt>Accession Year</dt>
              <dd>1979</dd>
            
            <dt>Object Number</dt>
            <dd>1979.110</dd>

                          <dt>Division</dt>
              <dd>European and American Art</dd>
            
                          <dt>Contact</dt>
              <dd><a href="mailto:am_europeanamerican@harvard.edu"><span>am_europeanamerican@harvard.edu</span></a></dd>
                               		  <dd>The Harvard Art Museums encourage the use of images found on this website for personal, noncommercial use, including educational and scholarly purposes. To request a higher resolution file of this image, please submit an <a href="https://www.harvardartmuseums.org/imagerequest"><span>online request.</span></a></dd>
          </dl>
        </dd>

        
                  <dt>Publication History</dt>
          <dd>
                                        <p>
                                              <em>Dessins, Anciens et Modernes: Collection de M. Louis Dimier</em>, auct. cat., Hôtel Drouot (Paris, December 15, 1921), p. 17, lot 31 [as by Goya], repr.
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              David P. Becker, <em>Drawings for Book Illustration: The Hofer Collection</em>, exh. cat., Houghton Library (Cambridge, 1980), under no. 22, p. 38
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              <em>Eugene Delacroix: Themen und Variationen, Arbeiten auf Papier</em>, exh. cat., Stadtische Galerie im Stadelschen Kunstinstitut (Frankfurt, 1987), p. 6, cat. no. A2
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Agnes Mongan, <em>David to Corot: French Drawings in the Fogg Art Museum</em>, Harvard University Press (Cambridge, MA, 1996), cat. no. 104, repr.
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Gary Tinterow and Geneviève Lacambre, <em>Manet/Velázquez: The French Taste for Spanish Painting</em>, exh. cat., Metropolitan Museum of Art / Yale University Press (New York, NY and London, England, 2003), cat. no. 117, fig. 6.8, p. 167
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              [Reproduction only], From Enlightenment to Romanticism, c. 1780-1830: Illustrations Book, Blocks 4-7, The Open University (Milton Keynes, England, 2004)., plate 32.26
                             </p>
                                                      <p>
                                              Sébastien Allard and Côme Fabre, <em>Delacroix</em>, exh. cat., The Metropolitan Museum of Art (New York, 2018), cat. no. 11, repr. p. 54
                             </p>
                                    </dd>
        
                  <dt>Exhibition History</dt>
          <dd>
                          <p>
                              <em>Delacroix</em>, The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York, 09/17/2018 - 01/06/2019
                            </p>
                      </dd>
        
        

        
      
      
        
